name="date-added">2023-08-18</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  In the words of <fr:link
href="martin-escardo.xml"
type="local"
addr="martin-escardo">Martín Escardó</fr:link>:

</fr:p><fr:blockquote><fr:p>
    A <fr:em>domain</fr:em> is a set of concrete finite elements together with infinite,
    ideal elements such that the ideal elements are characterized uniquely by
    their finite approximations.
  </fr:p></fr:blockquote><fr:p>
  There are different ways of capturing this mathematically, to varying
  degrees of precision. These include <fr:link
href="axt-001T.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001T">continuous</fr:link> and
  <fr:link
href="axt-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-001S">algebraic</fr:link> dcpos.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
